04368nam a22005655i 9780887553639DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20042004xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808875536397 a10.1515/97808875536392doi  a(DE-B1597)664713  a(OCoLC)1408682314  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxcCA 7aHIS0060202bisacsh04a307.721 aGiffen, James P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRural Life :bPortraits of the Prairie Town, 1946 /cJames P. Giffen; ed. by Gerald Friesen. 1aWinnipeg, Manitoba : bUniversity of Manitoba Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (282 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tElgin -- tRossburn -- tCarman -- tConclusion -- tStuart Garson, Harold Innis, and Adult Education in Manitoba -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the 1940s, the Manitoba Royal Commission on Adult Education investigated directions for the modernization of the province in the post-war era of change. It was charged particularly with looking at rural Manitoba’s cultural, educational, and leadership opportunities in the wake of new technologies, dwindling populations, and altered political and social affiliations. The commission engaged Jim Giffen, then a young sociologist from the University of Toronto, to undertake a detailed field study of three rural Manitoba towns in this context.Giffen’s extensive study examined the towns of Carman, Elgin, and Rossburn, all significantly different in terms of their ethnic makeup and level of political and organizational sophistication. He remained in the province for a year and a half, at the end of which his report, an analysis of “education for leadership,” was considered “too revealing” for public release. It remained in the Ontario Legislative Library until it was retrieved, 50 years later, by well-known historian Gerald Friesen, who has written an extensive postscript to the report.As a snapshot of rural agricultural life in prairie Canada at a time of great change, the study is invaluable. Despite the differences in the three towns, they retain some common characteristics that define a particular socio-cultural view of the larger world. Giffen looks at characteristics such as leadership in the community, ethnic differences, hierarchy of roles, participation in organizations, and aims and activities of young people. Friesen’s postscript provides a wider context to this study, and an assessment of what these differences and commonalities meant to the province.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCities and townsxCase studiesxPrairie Provinces. 0aSociologie ruralexProvinces des Prairies. 0aSociology, RuralxPrairie Provinces. 0aVillesxCas, Études dexProvinces des Prairies. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh1 aFriesen, Gerald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriesen, Gerald, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755363940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887553639423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887553639/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles